"# Chapter 1 — Before writing there were tallies

Long before somebody wrote a book, somebody counted.

We know this because we have the bones.

## The Ishango bone

In 1960 a Belgian geologist named Jean de Heinzelin de Braucourt was
digging near the headwaters of the Nile in what is now the Democratic
Republic of the Congo. He found a small piece of baboon fibula — that's
a leg bone — with tally marks scratched into it in three rows. The bone
is dated to about 20,000 years ago. It is called the Ishango bone and
it lives in a museum in Brussels.

Nobody knows exactly what the marks meant. Some scholars think they are
a lunar calendar. Some think they are a multiplication reference. Some
think they are a running tally of something a person owned. All the
theories share one word: **counting.**

Twenty thousand years ago, somebody had a reason to remember a number
and decided to record it in a way another person could read.

There is an older bone. The Lebombo bone, found on the border of Swaziland
and South Africa, is a piece of baboon fibula with 29 notches carved into
it. It is dated to about 43,000 years ago. Twenty-nine is roughly the
number of days in a lunar month. Somebody was maybe counting the moon.

That is the beginning of computing. Not a machine. A person, a bone, a
knife, and a reason.

## Why a tally

You know how to count. So did they. What the bone gives you that your
head does not is **persistence.** Your memory of ‘I have seven goats’
fades. A bone with seven notches on it doesn't. The notches are outside
your head. They will be there tomorrow. They will still be there for
your grandchild.

That is the first computing idea in the whole book: **put the state on
something more reliable than your memory.** Every hard drive, every log
file, every database, every backup does the same thing the bone did.
Externalize the state. Trust the medium more than the mind.

We will come back to that idea forever.

## The tally in ASCII

Here is a tally of seven, the classic four-and-a-cross-stroke:

```
     |    |    |
     |    |    |
   //|  //|  //|   .
    /|   /|   /|  /|
     |    |    |   |
     |    |    |   |
```

That is one hand plus two more. The cross-stroke lets you read groups
of five at a glance without recounting. Somebody in a market added the
cross-stroke and saved the world some time.

## The abacus — a bead is a bit

Fast forward. The Sumerians used stones in trays around 3000 BC. The
Chinese refined the counting-frame into what we call the abacus by about
the 2nd century BC. The Romans had one too. The Japanese soroban is
still sold in stores today.

An abacus is a rack of rods with beads. Each rod is a decimal place.
Each bead is a count. To add 27 and 15, you slide beads. To carry, you
clear a rod and push a bead one rod to the left. No electricity, no
transistors, no software. A four-year-old can be taught to use one.

An abacus is the same shape as a modern computer's arithmetic. Both use
positional notation. Both carry when a place overflows. The abacus is
base ten. The computer is base two. The mechanism is otherwise identical.

Here is a small ASCII abacus showing the number 42:

```
   thousands   hundreds   tens     ones
   ----------  --------   ------   ------
     .          .            *       * *
     .          .            *
     .          .            *
     .          .            *
     .          .
   ==========================================
     .          .          . . . .   . . .
     .          .          . . . .   . . .
```

Four beads pushed up in the tens column (that's 40). Two beads pushed up
in the ones column (that's 2). Read them: 42.

## The quipu — memory in string

Around AD 1400, the Inca Empire ran an empire the size of Europe with no
writing at all. They ran it on knotted strings called quipus. A quipu is
a main cord with hundreds of colored strings hanging off it, each with
different kinds of knots at different heights along the string.

The knots encoded numbers. Position along the string encoded place value.
Color encoded category (grain vs. cloth vs. people). A trained quipu-reader
could pick up somebody else's quipu and read the census of a valley.

Nobody was doing arithmetic on the quipu the way you do on an abacus. It
was a data storage medium. The externalized state again. A hard drive
made of alpaca wool.

## Now let us count in Motoi Scheme

The tally is the simplest data structure there is. In Scheme we can
represent it as a list. Adding a notch is `cons`. Reading the total is
`length`. Nothing fancy.

```
(define bone (list))                       ;; the fresh bone

(define bone (cons 'notch bone))           ;; carve one notch
(define bone (cons 'notch bone))           ;; carve another
(define bone (cons 'notch bone))           ;; and a third

(length bone)                              ;; => 3
```

That is a tally counter. Every notch is a symbol we picked (`notch`, but
it could be anything — Motoi doesn't care). Every carving is a `cons`
onto the front of the list. Reading the total is `length`.

If you want a proper counter — one you can increment without rewriting
the variable — Motoi Scheme has an idiom for that too:

```
(define (make-tally)
  (let ((count 0))
    (lambda ()
      (set! count (+ count 1))
      count)))

(define bone (make-tally))

(bone)   ;; => 1  (one notch)
(bone)   ;; => 2  (two notches)
(bone)   ;; => 3  (three notches)
(bone)   ;; => 4  (four notches)
```

That's a tally that lives inside a function. Each time you call `bone`,
it carves another notch and shows you the total. If we call `bone` a
million times, we get a million. If we call it once, we get one. The
mechanism is the same shape as the Ishango bone: state that persists
between events, updated by adding one.

## Grouping — cross-strokes in Scheme

Real tally counters group by five so you can eyeball a total. Let us
show groups of five:

```
(define (tally->groups notches)
  ;; break a flat list of notches into sublists of at most five.
  (let loop ((remaining notches) (groups '()) (current '()))
    (cond
      ((null? remaining)
       (reverse (if (null? current) groups (cons current groups))))
      ((= (length current) 5)
       (loop remaining
             (cons current groups)
             (list (car remaining))))
      (else
       (loop (cdr remaining)
             groups
             (cons (car remaining) current))))))

(tally->groups '(n n n n n n n n n n n n n))
;; => ((n n n n n) (n n n n n) (n n n))
```

Thirteen notches — two full groups of five, plus three left over. Same
idea as the cross-stroke on paper. Grouping is just a way to make counts
easier to read.

## The Roman numeral is a tally with rules

Somebody eventually wanted to write down bigger numbers without carving
a hundred notches. Roman numerals are a stylised tally. `I` is one notch.
`V` is five notches (the classic cross-stroke bundle). `X` is two `V`s
crossed. `L`, `C`, `D`, `M` are the next places up. Same story: each
symbol groups a bundle of smaller symbols.

Roman numerals are terrible for arithmetic (try multiplying `XLII` by
`XVII` in your head), and this is why they got replaced by the
Hindu-Arabic system — the one you use every day — around the 12th and
13th centuries in Europe. The Hindu-Arabic system uses **position**:
the `2` in `42` means twenty because it sits in the tens place. That is
a much better arrangement for arithmetic, and every calculator ever made
uses positional notation because of it. The abacus was the physical
version of it. Modern binary arithmetic is the same thing again, in
base two.

## What we take from the bone

Three ideas we will carry through the whole book:

1. **Persistence:** state lives outside the mind. Bone, string, disk.
2. **Grouping:** organize counts into bundles so a person or a machine
   can read them at a glance. Cross-strokes, place values, bytes, words.
3. **The count is the first computation.** Everything else — addition,
   subtraction, multiplication, division, algebra, logic, silicon, LLMs
   — is built on top of the count.

A person 20,000 years ago figured out idea 1 and idea 3. The abacus
added idea 2. The rest of this book is idea 2 getting fancier and fancier
until it produces the machine you're reading this on.

## The loop appears

Every tally is a loop. You do a thing — carve a notch. You wait for the
next event. You do the thing again. The `make-tally` function above is
that loop dressed up as a Scheme closure.

Loops will show up in every chapter of this book. Chapter 12 (the CPU)
and Appendix E are especially loop-heavy. Watch for them.

## Next

Now that we can count, we need something to add. Addition needs rules.
The rules of yes-and-no are called Boolean logic. Chapter 2.
")
